Assigment No: 1

Contribution:
I worked solo on this assignment, by coding reg.py and regdetails.py as specified in the course website. reg.py start by parsing arguments using argparse (sending errors when needed). Then, it creates a SQL prepared statement that is customized to the optional arguments received (using string concatenation). It then checks whether the database is in the current directory, and if so, queries the data. The program ends by printing out the classes that match the search, using the text wrap library for proper formatting.

regdetails.py has a similar execution, except that it does a more complex query for getting all the columns needed. Note that if the id given to the program does not match to a valid classid, regdetails.py yields an error message and returns. Otherwise, the data is fetched and printed in the specified format.

For testing, I wrote automated test files testreg.py and testregdetails.py, that compare the output of reg.py and regdetails.py with their respective reference programs. I used the system module and diff command for these comparisons, which prints the differences to stdout. These automated tests also perform coverage testing for the regular cases, and I finished coverage for boundary tests by writing the commands on the terminal.

External help:
I received no external help in this assignment.

